# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fm-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Developed in the 1960s by researchers at Stanford University, then commercialized through digital instruments such as the Yamaha GS-1 and popularized by the Yamaha DX7 in the 1980s, FM synthesis has had a lasting influence on recorded music, electronic music, popular music, and video game music.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It became closely associated with the sound of the 1980s, while related Yamaha FM chips gave many arcade games, home computers, game consoles, sound cards, and early mobile phone ringtones their characteristic timbres.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Its spread from Stanford University computer-music research into studios, homes, arcades, and consumer devices has made FM synthesis one of the most widely heard forms of digital synthesis of the late-20th century.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis can create both harmonic and inharmonic sounds.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] To synthesize harmonic sounds, the modulating signal must have a harmonic relationship to the original carrier signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] As the amount of frequency modulation increases, the sound grows progressively complex.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Through the use of modulators with frequencies that are non-integer multiples of the carrier signal (i.e. inharmonic), inharmonic bell-like and percussive spectra can be created.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis using analog oscillators may result in pitch instability.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] However, FM synthesis can also be implemented digitally, which is more stable and became standard practice.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Digital FM synthesis (equivalent to phase modulation using the time integration of instantaneous frequency) was the basis of several musical instruments beginning as early as 1974.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha built the first prototype digital synthesizer in 1974, based on FM synthesis, before commercially releasing the Yamaha GS-1 in 1980.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Synclavier I, manufactured by New England Digital Corporation beginning in 1978, had an optional digital FM synthesis module (later built into the Synclavier II) which could be added on to the synthesizer, using an FM synthesis algorithm licensed from Yamaha.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha's groundbreaking Yamaha DX7 synthesizer, released in 1983, brought FM to the forefront of synthesis in the mid-1980s.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis also became the usual setting for games and software up until the mid-nineties.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Sound cards for IBM PC compatible systems like the AdLib and Sound Blaster popularized Yamaha chips like the OPL2 and OPL3.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Other computers such as the Sharp X68000 and MSX (Yamaha CX5M computer unit) utilize the OPM sound chip (with later CX5M units using the similar OPP sound chip).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The NEC PC-88 and PC-98 computers use either the OPN and OPNA sound chips.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] For arcade systems and game consoles, the OPM was widely used in many arcade boards from the 1980s and 1990s (including Sega's System 16 and Capcom's CP System arcade boards); the similar OPN was also used in some arcade boards in the 1980s.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] OPNB was notably used in SNK's Neo Geo arcade (MVS) and home console (AES) machines, as well as being used as the main basic sound generator in Taito's arcade boards (with a variant of the OPNB being used in several arcade boards such as the Taito Z System board).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The related OPN2 was used in Sega's Mega Drive (Genesis), Fujitsu's FM Towns Marty, and some of Sega's arcade boards (e.g.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Sega System C-2 and Sega System 32) as one of its sound generator chips.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis was also used on a wide range of mobile phones in the 2000s to play ringtones and other sounds, using the Yamaha SMAF format.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Don Buchla implemented FM on his instruments in the mid-1960s, prior to Chowning's patent.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] His 158, 258 and 259 dual oscillator modules had a specific FM control voltage input, and the model 208 (Music Easel) had a modulation oscillator hard-wired to allow FM as well as AM of the primary oscillator.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] These early applications used analog oscillators, and this capability was also followed by other modular synthesizers and portable synthesizers including Minimoog and ARP Odyssey.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] By the mid-20th century, frequency modulation (FM), a means of carrying sound, had been understood for decades and was being used to broadcast radio transmissions.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis was developed since 1967 at Stanford University, California, by John Chowning, through his exploration of digital synthesis and spatialization, inspired by the new possibilities of digital sound as described by Max Mathews.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] His algorithm was licensed to Japanese company Yamaha in 1973.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The implementation commercialized by Yamaha (US Patent 4018121 Apr 1977 or U.S.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Patent 4,018,121) is actually based on phase modulation, but the results end up being equivalent mathematically as both are essentially a special case of quadrature amplitude modulation.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] In the 1970s, Yamaha were granted a number of patents, under the company's former name "Nippon Gakki Seizo Kabushiki Kaisha", evolving Chowning's work.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha built the first prototype FM digital synthesizer in 1974.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha eventually commercialized FM synthesis technology with the Yamaha GS-1, the first FM digital synthesizer, released in 1980.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis was the basis of some of the early generations of digital synthesizers, most notably those from Yamaha, as well as New England Digital Corporation under license from Yamaha.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha's DX7 synthesizer, released in 1983, was ubiquitous throughout the 1980s.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha had patented its hardware implementation of FM in the 1970s, allowing it to nearly monopolize the market for FM technology until the mid-1990s.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Casio developed a related form of synthesis called phase distortion synthesis, used in its CZ range of synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It had a similar (but slightly differently derived) sound quality to the DX series.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] With the expiration of the Stanford University FM patent in 1995, digital FM synthesis can now be implemented freely by other manufacturers.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The FM synthesis patent brought Stanford $20 million before it expired, making it (in 1994) "the second most lucrative licensing agreement in Stanford's history".
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The degree of complexity of the FM in such hardware synths may vary from simple 2-operator FM, to the highly flexible 6-operator engines of the Korg Kronos and Alesis Fusion, to creation of FM in extensively modular engines such as those in the latest synthesisers by Kurzweil Music Systems.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Yamaha SY77, Yamaha SY99 and FS1R synthesizers marketed their highly powerful FM abilities as counterparts to sample-based synthesis and formant synthesis respectively.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Various other synthesizers offer limited FM abilities to supplement their main engines.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The FS1R had 16 operators, 8 standard FM operators and 8 additional operators that used a noise source rather than an oscillator as its sound source.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] By adding in tuneable noise sources the FS1R could model the sounds produced in the human voice and in a wind instrument, along with making percussion instrument sounds.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The FS1R also contained an additional wave form called the Formant wave form.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Formants can be used to model resonating body instrument sounds like the cello, violin, acoustic guitar, bassoon, English horn, or human voice.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Formants can even be found in the harmonic spectrum of several brass instruments.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] In 2016, Korg released the Korg Volca FM, a, 3-voice, 6 operators FM iteration of the Korg Volca series of compact, affordable desktop modules.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Korg has also released the opsix (2020) and opsix SE (2023), integrating 6 operators FM synthesis with subtractive, analogue modeling, additive, semi-modular and Waveshaping.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha released the Montage in 2016, which combines a 128-voice sample-based engine with a 128-voice FM engine.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] This iteration of FM is called FM-X, and features 8 operators; each operator has a choice of several basic wave forms, but each wave form has several parameters to adjust its spectrum.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It was then followed by the more affordable Yamaha MODX in 2018, with 64-voice, 8 operators FM-X architecture in addition to a 128-voice sample-based engine.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The MODX+ released in 2022 increased the number of voices of the FM-X engine to 128, the same as with the Montage.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Montage was succeeded by the Montage M in 2023, which uses the same 128-voice, 8 operators FM-X engine alongside a 128-voice sample-based engine and a newly introduced 16-voice 3 oscillator analog-based engine known as AN-X.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Elektron launched the Digitone in 2018, which is an 8-voice, 4 operators FM synth featuring Elektron's renowned sequence engine.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM-X synthesis was first introduced with the Yamaha Montage synthesizers in 2016.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Each FM-X operator has a set of multi-spectral wave forms to choose from, which means each FM-X operator can be equivalent to a stack of 3 or 4 DX7 FM operators.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The list of selectable wave forms includes sine waves, the All1 and All2 wave forms, the Odd1 and Odd2 wave forms, and the Res1 and Res2 wave forms.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The sine wave selection works the same as the DX7 wave forms.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The All1 and All2 wave forms are a saw-tooth wave form.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Odd1 and Odd2 wave forms are pulse or square waves.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] These two types of wave forms can be used to model the basic harmonic peaks in the bottom of the harmonic spectrum of most instruments.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Res1 and Res2 wave forms move the spectral peak to a specific harmonic and can be used to model either triangular or rounded groups of harmonics further up in the spectrum of an instrument.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Combining an All1 or Odd1 wave form with multiple Res1 (or Res2) wave forms (and adjusting their amplitudes) can model the harmonic spectrum of an instrument or sound.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Combining sets of 8 FM operators with multi-spectral wave forms was first introduced in the FS1R, released in 1999 by Yamaha.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It was able to achieve similar results to that of FM-X using 8 noise operators.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] As the basic of these variations, we analyze the spectrum of 2 operators (linear FM synthesis using two sinusoidal operators) on the following.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] If we were to ignore the constant phase terms on the carrier $\phi _{c}=B/\omega _{m}\,$ and the modulator $\phi _{m}=-\pi /2\,$ , finally we would get the following expression, as seen on Chowning 1973 and Roads 1996, p.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] where $\omega _{c}\,,\,\omega _{m}\,$ are angular frequencies ( $\,\omega =2\pi f\,$ ) of carrier and modulator, $\beta =B/\omega _{m}\,$ is frequency modulation index, and amplitudes $J_{n}(\beta )\,$ is $n\,$ -th Bessel function of first kind, respectively.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In analog frequency modulation, such as radio broadcasting of voice and music, the instantaneous frequency deviation, i.e. the difference between the frequency of the carrier and its center frequency, has a functional relation to the modulating signal amplitude.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Digital data can be encoded and transmitted using a form of frequency modulation known as frequency-shift keying (FSK), in which the frequency of a carrier is switched among a discrete set of values.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In its simplest form, binary FSK, two frequencies represent binary symbols 0 and 1.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FSK is widely used in low to moderate data-rate applications because of its simplicity and robustness.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Common uses include early computer modems (such as fax modems), telephone caller-ID systems, garage-door openers, remote keyless entry systems, and radioteletype.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency modulation is widely used for FM broadcasting.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] It is also used in telemetry, radar, seismic prospecting, and monitoring newborns for seizures via EEG, two-way radio systems, sound synthesis, magnetic tape-recording systems and some video-transmission systems.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In radio transmission, an advantage of frequency modulation is that it has a larger signal-to-noise ratio and therefore rejects radio frequency interference better than an equal power amplitude modulation (AM) signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For this reason, most music is broadcast over FM radio.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency modulation and phase modulation are the two complementary principal methods of angle modulation; phase modulation is often used as an intermediate step to achieve frequency modulation.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] These methods contrast with amplitude modulation, in which the amplitude of the carrier wave varies, while the frequency and phase remain constant.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] According to Paul Nahin, "To apply the baseband signal of a microphone output directly to the transmitter antenna won't work, because ...a quarter-wavelength antenna at audio frequencies is physically enormous.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] To have a reasonably sized antenna requires a transmitter signal at frequencies considerably higher than those of the bandwidth spectrum; that is, the baseband spectrum must be upshifted to the radio frequencies." This is called signal modulation.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] According to Ron Bertrand, "Frequency modulation is a method of modulating a carrier wave whereby the modulating audio causes the instantaneous frequency of the carrier to change.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The amplitude factor kAωa defines the maximum Frequency deviation around ωc.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] While most of the energy of the signal is contained within *fc* ± *f*Δ, it can be shown by Fourier analysis that a wider range of frequencies is required to precisely represent an FM signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The frequency spectrum of an actual FM signal has components extending infinitely, although their amplitude decreases and higher-order components are often neglected in practical design problems.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Mathematically, a baseband modulating signal may be approximated by a sinusoidal continuous wave signal with a frequency *fm*.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] This method is also named as single-tone modulation.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] where the amplitude $A_{m}\,$ of the modulating sinusoid is represented in the peak deviation $f_{\Delta }=K_{f}A_{m}$ (see frequency deviation).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The harmonic distribution of a sine wave carrier modulated by such a sinusoidal signal can be represented with Bessel functions; this provides the basis for a mathematical understanding of frequency modulation in the frequency domain.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] As in other modulation systems, the modulation index indicates by how much the modulated variable varies around its unmodulated level.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] where $f_{m}\,$ is the highest frequency component present in the modulating signal *x**m*(*t*), and $\Delta {}f\,$ is the peak frequency-deviation – i.e. the maximum deviation of the *instantaneous frequency* from the carrier frequency.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For a sine wave modulation, the modulation index is seen to be the ratio of the peak frequency deviation of the carrier wave to the frequency of the modulating sine wave.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] If $h\ll 1$ , the modulation is called **narrowband FM** (NFM), and its bandwidth is approximately $2f_{m}\,$ .
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Sometimes modulation index $h<0.3$ is considered NFM and other modulation indices are considered wideband FM (WFM or FM).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] where $T_{s}\,$ is the symbol period, and $f_{m}={\frac {1}{2T_{s}}}\,$ is used as the highest frequency of the modulating binary waveform by convention, even though it would be more accurate to say it is the highest *fundamental* of the modulating binary waveform.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In the case of digital modulation, the carrier $f_{c}\,$ is never transmitted.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Rather, one of two frequencies is transmitted, either $f_{c}+\Delta f$ or $f_{c}-\Delta f$ , depending on the binary state 0 or 1 of the modulation signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] If $h\gg 1$ , the modulation is called *wideband FM* and its bandwidth is approximately $2f_{\Delta }\,$ .
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] While wideband FM uses more bandwidth, it can improve the signal-to-noise ratio significantly; for example, doubling the value of $\Delta {}f\,$ , while keeping $f_{m}$ constant, results in an eight-fold improvement in the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] (Compare this with chirp spread spectrum, which uses extremely wide frequency deviations to achieve processing gains comparable to traditional, better-known spread-spectrum modes).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] With a tone-modulated FM wave, if the modulation frequency is held constant and the modulation index is increased, the (non-negligible) bandwidth of the FM signal increases but the spacing between spectra remains the same; some spectral components decrease in strength as others increase.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] If the frequency deviation is held constant and the modulation frequency increased, the spacing between spectra increases.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency modulation can be classified as narrowband if the change in the carrier frequency is about the same as the signal frequency, or as wideband if the change in the carrier frequency is much higher (modulation index > 1) than the signal frequency.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For example, narrowband FM (NFM) is used for two-way radio systems such as Family Radio Service, in which the carrier is allowed to deviate only 2.5 kHz above and below the center frequency with speech signals of no more than 3.5 kHz bandwidth.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Wideband FM is used for FM broadcasting, in which music and speech are transmitted with up to 75 kHz deviation from the center frequency and carry audio with up to a 20 kHz bandwidth and subcarriers up to 92 kHz.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In his 1922 FM paper, Carson pointed out an infinite number of side frequencies are generated when a carrier frequency is modulated by a signal frequency, the amplitudes expressed as Bessel functions.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The separation is determined by the frequency of the modulating signal, and the amplitude dependent upon the modulation index.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] A table of Bessel functions of the first kind is used to determine the side frequency amplitudes.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For the case of a carrier modulated by a single sine wave, the resulting frequency spectrum can be calculated using Bessel functions of the first kind, as a function of the sideband number and the modulation index.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The carrier and sideband amplitudes are illustrated for different modulation indices of FM signals.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For particular values of the modulation index, the carrier amplitude becomes zero and all the signal power is in the sidebands.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Since the sidebands are on both sides of the carrier, their count is doubled, and then multiplied by the modulating frequency to find the bandwidth.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For example, 3 kHz deviation modulated by a 2.2 kHz audio tone produces a modulation index of 1.36.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Suppose that we limit ourselves to only those sidebands that have a relative amplitude of at least 0.01.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Then, examining the chart shows this modulation index will produce three sidebands.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] These three sidebands, when doubled, gives us (6 × 2.2 kHz) or a 13.2 kHz required bandwidth.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Carson's rule can only be applied to sinusoidal signals.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] where W is the highest frequency in the modulating signal but non-sinusoidal in nature and D is the Deviation ratio which is the ratio of frequency deviation to highest frequency of modulating non-sinusoidal signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM provides improved signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), as compared for example with AM.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Compared with an optimum AM scheme, FM typically has poorer SNR below a certain signal level called the noise threshold, but above a higher level – the full improvement or full quieting threshold – the SNR is much improved over AM.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The improvement depends on modulation level and deviation.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For typical voice communications channels, improvements are typically 5–15 dB.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM broadcasting using wider deviation can achieve even greater improvements.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Additional techniques, such as pre-emphasis of higher audio frequencies with corresponding de-emphasis in the receiver, are generally used to improve overall SNR in FM circuits.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Since FM signals have constant amplitude, FM receivers normally have limiters that remove AM noise, further improving SNR.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] A common method for recovering the information signal is through a Foster–Seeley discriminator or ratio detector.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] A phase-locked loop can be used as an FM demodulator.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] *Slope detection* demodulates an FM signal by using a tuned circuit which has its resonant frequency slightly offset from the carrier.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The input FM wave of constant amplitude and instantaneous frequency, is converted to an FM wave with instantaneous frequency and instantaneous amplitude, which is then sent to an envelop detector.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] AM receivers may detect some FM transmissions by this means, although it does not provide an efficient means of detection for FM broadcasts.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In software-defined radio implementations, the demodulation may be carried out by using the Hilbert transform (implemented as a filter) to recover the instantaneous phase, and thereafter differentiating this phase (using another filter) to recover the instantaneous frequency.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Alternatively, a complex mixer followed by a bandpass filter may be used to translate the signal to baseband, and then proceeding as before.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For sampled signals, phase detection, and therefore frequency modulation detection, can be approximated by taking the IQ (complex) sample and multiplying it with the complex conjugate of the previous IQ sample, $x[n]\cdot {\overline {x[n-1]}}$ .
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] If the demodulated signal is sampled at or above Nyquist, this allows for recovery of near-instantaneous phase changes.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In 1968, Schnitzler noted certain bats lower the echolocation emission frequency by 13 to 16 kHz, compensating for Doppler shifts caused by the bat’s own movement.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Doppler shift compensation, dynamic frequency modulation, ensures that the returning echo frequency is optimally adjusted for the bat's auditory fovea.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM is also used at intermediate frequencies by analog VCR systems (including VHS) to record the luminance (black and white) portions of the video signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Commonly, the chrominance component is recorded as a conventional AM signal, using the higher-frequency FM signal as bias.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM also keeps the tape at saturation level, acting as a form of noise reduction; a limiter can mask variations in playback output, and the FM capture effect removes print-through and pre-echo.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] A continuous pilot-tone, if added to the signal – as was done on V2000 and many Hi-band formats – can keep mechanical jitter under control and assist timebase correction.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] These FM systems are unusual, in that they have a ratio of carrier to maximum modulation frequency of less than two; contrast this with FM audio broadcasting, where the ratio is around 10,000.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Consider, for example, a 6-MHz carrier modulated at a 3.5-MHz rate; by Bessel analysis, the first sidebands are on 9.5 and 2.5 MHz and the second sidebands are on 13 MHz and −1 MHz.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The result is a reversed-phase sideband on +1 MHz; on demodulation, this results in unwanted output at 6 – 1 = 5 MHz.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The system must be designed so that this unwanted output is reduced to an acceptable level.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM is also used at audio frequencies to synthesize sound.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] This technique, known as FM synthesis, was popularized by early digital synthesizers and became a standard feature in several generations of personal computer sound cards.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Edwin Howard Armstrong (1890–1954) was an American electrical engineer who invented wideband frequency modulation (FM) radio.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] He patented the regenerative circuit in 1914, the superheterodyne receiver in 1918 and the super-regenerative circuit in 1922.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Armstrong presented his paper, "A Method of Reducing Disturbances in Radio Signaling by a System of Frequency Modulation", (which first described FM radio) before the New York section of the Institute of Radio Engineers on November 6, 1935.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The first experimental station, W2XMN, went on the air in 1937.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] As the name implies, wideband FM (WFM) requires a wider signal bandwidth than amplitude modulation by an equivalent modulating signal; this also makes the signal more robust against noise and interference.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency modulation is also more robust against signal-amplitude-fading phenomena.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] As a result, FM was chosen as the modulation standard for high frequency, high fidelity radio transmission, hence the term "FM radio" (although for many years the BBC called it "VHF radio" because commercial FM broadcasting uses part of the VHF band – the FM broadcast band).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency drift or a lack of selectivity may cause one station to be overtaken by another on an adjacent channel.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency drift was a problem in early (or inexpensive) receivers; inadequate selectivity may affect any tuner.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] A wideband FM signal can also be used to carry a stereo signal; this is done with multiplexing and demultiplexing before and after the FM process.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] The FM modulation and demodulation process is identical in stereo and monaural processes.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM is commonly used at VHF radio frequencies for high-fidelity broadcasts of music and speech.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In broadcast services, where audio fidelity is important, wideband FM is generally used.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Analog TV sound is also broadcast using FM.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Narrowband FM is used for voice communications in commercial and amateur radio settings.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] In two-way radio, narrowband FM (NBFM) is used to conserve bandwidth for land mobile, marine mobile and other radio services.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] A high-efficiency radio-frequency switching amplifier can be used to transmit FM signals (and other constant-amplitude signals).
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For a given signal strength (measured at the receiver antenna), switching amplifiers use less battery power and typically cost less than a linear amplifier.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] This gives FM another advantage over other modulation methods requiring linear amplifiers, such as AM and QAM.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] There are reports that on October 5, 1924, Professor Mikhail A.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Bonch-Bruevich, during a scientific and technical conversation in the Nizhny Novgorod Radio Laboratory, reported about his new method of telephony, based on a change in the period of oscillations.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Demonstration of frequency modulation was carried out on the laboratory model.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] Frequency modulated systems are a widespread and commercially available assistive technology that make speech more understandable by improving the signal-to-noise ratio in the user's ear.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] They are also called *auditory trainers*, a term which refers to any sound amplification system not classified as a hearing aid.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] They intensify signal levels from the source by 15 to 20 decibels.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM systems are used by hearing-impaired people as well as children whose listening is affected by disorders such as auditory processing disorder or ADHD.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] For people with sensorineural hearing loss, FM systems result in better speech perception than hearing aids.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] They can be coupled with behind-the-ear hearing aids to allow the user to alternate the setting.
[src:fm-synthesis/frequency-modulation] FM systems are more convenient and cost-effective than alternatives such as cochlear implants, but many users use FM systems infrequently due to their conspicuousness and need for recharging.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The term *vibration* is precisely used to describe a mechanical oscillation.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Oscillation, especially rapid oscillation, may be an undesirable phenomenon in process control and control theory (e.g. in sliding mode control), where the aim is convergence to stable state.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In these cases it is called chattering or flapping, as in valve chatter, and route flapping.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The simplest mechanical oscillating system is a weight attached to a linear spring subject to only weight and tension.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Such a system may be approximated on an air table or ice surface.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The system is in an equilibrium state when the spring is static.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] If the system is displaced from the equilibrium, there is a net *restoring force* on the mass, tending to bring it back to equilibrium.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] However, in moving the mass back to the equilibrium position, it has acquired momentum which keeps it moving beyond that position, establishing a new restoring force in the opposite sense.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] If a constant force such as gravity is added to the system, the point of equilibrium is shifted.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The time taken for an oscillation to occur is often referred to as the oscillatory *period*.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The systems where the restoring force on a body is directly proportional to its displacement, such as the dynamics of the spring-mass system, are described mathematically by the simple harmonic oscillator and the regular periodic motion is known as simple harmonic motion.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In the spring-mass system, oscillations occur because, at the static equilibrium displacement, the mass has kinetic energy which is converted into potential energy stored in the spring at the extremes of its path.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The spring-mass system illustrates some common features of oscillation, namely the existence of an equilibrium and the presence of a restoring force which grows stronger the further the system deviates from equilibrium.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] where ω is the frequency of the oscillation, A is the amplitude, and δ is the phase shift of the function.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] These are determined by the initial conditions of the system.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Because cosine oscillates between 1 and −1 infinitely, our spring-mass system would oscillate between the positive and negative amplitude forever without friction.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In two or three dimensions, harmonic oscillators behave similarly to one dimension.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] With anisotropic oscillators, different directions have different constants of restoring forces.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The solution is similar to isotropic oscillators, but there is a different frequency in each direction.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Varying the frequencies relative to each other can produce interesting results.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] For example, if the frequency in one direction is twice that of another, a figure eight pattern is produced.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] If the ratio of frequencies is irrational, the motion is quasiperiodic.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This motion is periodic on each axis, but is not periodic with respect to r, and will never repeat.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] All real-world oscillator systems are thermodynamically irreversible.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This means there are dissipative processes such as friction or electrical resistance which continually convert some of the energy stored in the oscillator into heat in the environment.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Thus, oscillations tend to decay with time unless there is some net source of energy into the system.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The simplest description of this decay process can be illustrated by oscillation decay of the harmonic oscillator.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Damped oscillators are created when a resistive force is introduced, which is dependent on the first derivative of the position, or in this case velocity.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The differential equation created by Newton's second law adds in this resistive force with an arbitrary constant b.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The exponential term outside of the parenthesis is the decay function and β is the damping coefficient.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] There are 3 categories of damped oscillators: under-damped, where *β* < *ω*0; over-damped, where *β* > *ω*0; and critically damped, where *β* = *ω*0.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In addition, an oscillating system may be subject to some external force, as when an AC circuit is connected to an outside power source.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In this case the oscillation is said to be *driven*.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The second term of *x*(*t*) is the transient solution to the differential equation.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The transient solution can be found by using the initial conditions of the system.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Some systems can be excited by energy transfer from the environment.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This transfer typically occurs where systems are embedded in some fluid flow.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] At sufficiently large displacements, the stiffness of the wing dominates to provide the restoring force that enables an oscillation.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Resonance occurs in a damped driven oscillator when ω = ω0, that is, when the driving frequency is equal to the natural frequency of the system.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] When this occurs, the denominator of the amplitude is minimized, which maximizes the amplitude of the oscillations.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The harmonic oscillator and the systems it models have a single degree of freedom.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] More complicated systems have more degrees of freedom, for example, two masses and three springs (each mass being attached to fixed points and to each other).
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In such cases, the behavior of each variable influences that of the others.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This leads to a *coupling* of the oscillations of the individual degrees of freedom.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] For example, two pendulum clocks (of identical frequency) mounted on a common wall will tend to synchronise.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This phenomenon was first observed by Christiaan Huygens in 1665.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The apparent motions of the compound oscillations typically appears very complicated but a more economic, computationally simpler and conceptually deeper description is given by resolving the motion into normal modes.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The simplest form of coupled oscillators is a 3 spring, 2 mass system, where masses and spring constants are the same.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Depending on the starting point of the masses, this system has 2 possible frequencies (or a combination of the two).
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] If the masses are started with their displacements in the same direction, the frequency is that of a single mass system, because the middle spring is never extended.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] If the two masses are started in opposite directions, the second, faster frequency is the frequency of the system.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] More special cases are the coupled oscillators where energy alternates between two forms of oscillation.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Well-known is the Wilberforce pendulum, where the oscillation alternates between the elongation of a vertical spring and the rotation of an object at the end of that spring.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Coupled oscillators are a common description of two related, but different phenomena.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] One case is where both oscillations affect each other mutually, which usually leads to the occurrence of a single, entrained oscillation state, where both oscillate with a *compromise frequency*.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Another case is where one external oscillation affects an internal oscillation, but is not affected by this.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In this case the regions of synchronization, known as Arnold Tongues, can lead to highly complex phenomena as for instance chaotic dynamics.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] In physics, a system with a set of conservative forces and an equilibrium point can be approximated as a harmonic oscillator near equilibrium.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The system will undergo oscillations near the equilibrium point.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This approximation can be better understood by looking at the potential curve of the system.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] By thinking of the potential curve as a hill, in which, if one placed a ball anywhere on the curve, the ball would roll down with the slope of the potential curve.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] By thinking of the potential in this way, one will see that at any local minimum there is a "well" in which the ball would roll back and forth (oscillate) between $r_{\text{min}}$ and $r_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] This approximation is also useful for thinking of Kepler orbits.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] As the number of degrees of freedom becomes arbitrarily large, a system approaches continuity; examples include a string or the surface of a body of water.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] Such systems have (in the classical limit) an infinite number of normal modes and their oscillations occur in the form of waves that can characteristically propagate.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] The mathematics of oscillation deals with the quantification of the amount that a sequence or function tends to move between extremes.
[src:fm-synthesis/oscillator] There are several related notions: oscillation of a sequence of real numbers, oscillation of a real-valued function at a point, and oscillation of a function on an interval (or open set).
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] In phase modulation, the instantaneous amplitude of the baseband signal modifies the phase of the carrier signal keeping its amplitude and frequency constant.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] The phase of a carrier signal is modulated to follow the changing signal level (amplitude) of the message signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] The peak amplitude and the frequency of the carrier signal are maintained constant, but as the amplitude of the message signal changes, the phase of the carrier changes correspondingly.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] Phase modulation is an integral part of many digital transmission coding schemes that underlie a wide range of technologies like Wi-Fi, GSM and satellite television.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] However, it is not widely used for transmitting analog audio signals via radio waves, because of the relative complexity needed in the receiver, for no added benefit with audio signals.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] It is also used for signal and waveform generation in digital synthesizers, such as the Yamaha DX7, to implement FM synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] A related type of sound synthesis called phase distortion is used in the Casio CZ synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] The functional form of the cosine term, which contains the expression of the instantaneous phase $\omega t+\phi (t)$ as its argument, provides the distinction of the two types of angle modulation, frequency modulation (FM) and phase modulation (PM).
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] In FM the message signal causes a functional variation of the carrier frequency.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] These variations are controlled by both the frequency and the amplitude of the modulating wave.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] In phase modulation, the instantaneous phase deviation $\phi (t)$ (phase angle) of the carrier is controlled by the modulating waveform, such that the principal frequency remains constant.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] In principle, the modulating signal in frequency modulation or phase modulation may either be analog in nature, or it may be digital.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] The modulation index reflects the degree of variation of the modulated variable around its unmodulated level.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] where $\Delta \theta$ is the peak phase deviation.
[src:fm-synthesis/phase-modulation] Compare to the modulation index for frequency modulation.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A **synthesizer** (also **synthesiser** or **synth**) is an electronic musical instrument that generates audio signals.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers typically create sounds by generating waveforms through methods including subtractive synthesis, additive synthesis, and frequency modulation synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] These sounds may be altered by components such as filters, which cut or boost frequencies; envelopes, which control articulation, or how notes begin and end; and low-frequency oscillators, which modulate parameters such as pitch, volume, or filter characteristics affecting timbre.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are typically played with keyboards or controlled by sequencers, software or other instruments, and can be synchronized to other equipment via MIDI.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer-like instruments emerged in the United States in the mid-20th century with instruments such as the RCA Mark II, which was controlled with punch cards and used hundreds of vacuum tubes.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog synthesizer, developed by Robert Moog and first sold in 1964, is credited for pioneering concepts such as voltage-controlled oscillators, envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, the smaller, cheaper Minimoog standardized synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards, unlike the larger modular synthesizers before it.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, which used microprocessors to allow users to store sounds for the first time.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments, was introduced in 1982 and remains an industry standard.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, launched in 1983, was a major success and popularized digital synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Software synthesizers now can be run as plug-ins or embedded on microchips.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 21st century, analog synthesizers returned to popularity with the advent of cheaper manufacturing.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were initially viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and countercultural scenes but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968)*,* a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, took synthesizers to the mainstream.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They were adopted by electronic acts and pop and rock groups in the 1960s and 1970s and were widely used in 1980s music.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced genres such as electronic and hip hop music.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is used in nearly every genre and is considered one of the most important instruments in the music industry.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] As electricity became more widely available, the early 20th century saw the invention of electronic musical instruments including the Telharmonium, Trautonium, ondes Martenot and theremin.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1930s, the Hammond Organ Company built the Novachord, a large instrument powered by 72 voltage-controlled amplifiers and 146 vacuum tubes.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1948, the Canadian engineer Hugh Le Caine completed the electronic sackbut, a precursor to voltage-controlled synthesizers, with keyboard sensitivity allowing for vibrato, glissando, and attack control.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1957, Harry Olson and Herbert Belar completed the RCA Mark II Sound Synthesizer at the RCA laboratories in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The instrument read punched paper tape that controlled an analog synthesizer containing 750 vacuum tubes.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was acquired by the Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center and used almost exclusively by Milton Babbitt, a composer at Princeton University.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* define "the early years of the synthesizer" as between 1964 and the mid-1970s, beginning with the debut of the Moog synthesizer, designed by the American engineer Robert Moog.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was composed of separate modules connected by patch cables that generate, shape or control sound.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog developed a means of controlling pitch through voltage, the voltage-controlled oscillator.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This, along with Moog components such as envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers, became standard components in synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Around the same period, the American engineer Don Buchla created the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Instead of a conventional keyboard, Buchla's system used touchplates which transmitted control voltages depending on finger position and force.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, the Moog's keyboard made it more accessible and marketable to musicians, and keyboards became the standard means of controlling synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog and Buchla initially avoided the word *synthesizer* for their instruments, as it was associated with the RCA synthesizer; however, by the 1970s, it had become the standard term.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, Moog launched a cheaper, smaller synthesizer, the Minimoog.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was the first synthesizer sold in music stores, and was more practical for live performance.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It standardized the concept of synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the early 1970s, the British composer Ken Freeman introduced the first string synthesizer, designed to emulate string sections.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] After retail stores started selling synthesizers in 1971, other synthesizer companies were established, including ARP in the US and EMS in the UK.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP's products included the ARP 2600, which folded into a carrying case and had built-in speakers, and the Odyssey, a rival to the Minimoog.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The less expensive EMS synthesizers were used by European art rock and progressive rock acts including Brian Eno and Pink Floyd.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Designs for synthesizers appeared in the amateur electronics market, such as a design published in *Practical Electronics* in 1973.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] By the mid-1970s, ARP was the world's largest synthesizer manufacturer, though it closed in 1981.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were monophonic, meaning they could only play one note at a time.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Some of the earliest commercial polyphonic synthesizers were created by the American engineer Tom Oberheim, such as the OB-X (1979).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, the American company Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, the first fully programmable polyphonic synthesizer.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Whereas previous synthesizers required users to adjust cables and knobs to change sounds, with no guarantee of exactly recreating a sound, the Prophet-5 used microprocessors to store sounds in patch memory.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This facilitated a move from synthesizers creating unpredictable sounds to producing "a standard package of familiar sounds".
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The synthesizer market grew dramatically in the 1980s.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] 1982 saw the introduction of MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments; it remains an industry standard.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] An influential sampling synthesizer, the Fairlight CMI, was released in 1979, with the ability to record and play back samples at different pitches.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Though its high price made it inaccessible to amateurs, it was adopted by high-profile pop musicians including Kate Bush and Peter Gabriel.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The success of the Fairlight drove competition, improving sampling technology and lowering prices.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early competing samplers included the E-mu Emulator in 1981 and the Akai S-series in 1985.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1983, Yamaha released the first commercially successful digital synthesizer, the Yamaha DX7.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Based on frequency modulation (FM) synthesis developed by the Stanford University engineer John Chowning, the DX7 was characterized by its *harsh*, *glassy* and *chilly* sounds, compared to the *warm* and *fuzzy* sounds of analog synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 unitsand remains one of the bestselling in history.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Digital synthesizers typically contained preset sounds emulating acoustic instruments, with algorithms controlled with menus and buttons.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Synclavier, made with FM technology licensed from Yamaha, offered features such as 16-bit sampling and digital recording.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With a starting price of $13,000, its use was limited to universities, studios and wealthy artists.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Roland D-50 (1987) blended Roland's linear arithmetic algorithm with samples, and was the first mass-produced synthesizer with built-in digital effects such as delay, reverb and chorus.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1988, the Japanese manufacturer Korg released the M1, a digital synthesizer workstation featuring sampled transients and loops.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With more than 250,000 units sold, it remains the bestselling synthesizer in history.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The advent of digital synthesizers led to a downturn in interest in analog synthesizers in the following decade.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ReBirth by Propellerhead Software and Reality by Seer Systems, the first software synthesizers that could be played in real time via MIDI, were released in 1997.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1999, an update to the music software Cubase allowed users to run software instruments (including synthesizers) as plug-ins, triggering a wave of new software instruments.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Propellerhead's Reason, released in 2000, introduced an array of recognizable virtual studio equipment.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The market for patchable and modular synthesizers rebounded in the late 1990s.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2000s, older analog synthesizers regained popularity, sometimes selling for much more than their original prices.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2010s, new, affordable analog synthesizers were introduced by companies including Moog, Korg, Arturia and Dave Smith Instruments.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The renewed interest is credited to the appeal of imperfect *organic* sounds and simpler interfaces, and modern surface-mount technology making analog synthesizers cheaper and faster to manufacture.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and counter-cultural scenes for their ability to make new sounds, but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968), a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, demonstrated that synthesizers could be more than "random noise machines", taking them to the mainstream.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, debates were held about the appropriateness of synthesizers in baroque music, and according to the *Guardian* they were quickly abandoned in "serious classical circles".
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is one of the most important instruments in the music industry, used in nearly every genre.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It is considered by the authors of *Analog Days* as "the only innovation that can stand alongside the electric guitar as a great new instrument of the age of electricity ...
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was adopted by 1960s rock acts including the Doors, the Grateful Dead, the Rolling Stones, the Beatles, and Keith Emerson.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Emerson was the first major rock musician to perform with the Moog and it became a trademark of his performances, helping take his band Emerson, Lake & Palmer to global stardom.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] According to *Analog Days*, the likes of Emerson, with his Moog performances, "did for the keyboard what Jimi Hendrix did for the guitar".
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] String synthesizers were used by 1970s progressive rock bands including Camel, Caravan, Electric Light Orchestra, Gentle Giant and Renaissance.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The portable Minimoog (1970), much smaller than the modular synthesizers before it, made synthesizers more common in live performance.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers could only play one note at a time, making them suitable for basslines, leads and solos.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With the rise of polyphonic synthesizers in the 1970s and 1980s, "the keyboard in rock once more started to revert to the background, to be used for fills and atmosphere rather than for soloing".
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Queen included statements in their 1970s album notes specifying that no synthesisers had been used, but added them in their 1980 album *The Game*.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Minimoog took a place in mainstream African-American music, most notably in the work of Stevie Wonder, and in jazz, such as the work of Sun Ra.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1970s and the early 1980s, the Minimoog was widely used in the emerging disco genre by artists including Abba and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced all genres of music and had a major influence on the development of electronic and hip hop music.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s, electronic music composers such as Jean Michel Jarre and Isao Tomita released successful synthesizer-led instrumental albums.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This influenced the emergence of synth-pop from the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The sequencer-based Roland TB-303 (1981), in conjunction with the Roland TR-808 and TR-909 drum machines, became a foundation of electronic dance music genres such as house and techno when producers acquired cheap second-hand units later in the decade.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* connect the synthesizer's origins in 1960s psychedelia to the raves and British Second Summer of Love of the 1980s and the club scenes of the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Gary Numan's 1979 hits "Are 'Friends' Electric?" and "Cars" made heavy use of synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] OMD's "Enola Gay" (1980) used distinctive electronic percussion and a synthesized melody.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Soft Cell used a synthesized melody on their 1981 hit "Tainted Love".
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Nick Rhodes, the keyboardist of Duran Duran, used synthesizers including the Roland Jupiter-4 and Jupiter-8.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Chart hits include Depeche Mode's "Just Can't Get Enough" (1981), the Human League's "Don't You Want Me" and works by Ultravox.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, digital synthesizers were widely used in pop music.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, released in 1983, became a pop staple, used on songs by A-ha, Kenny Loggins, Kool & the Gang.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Its E PIANO 1 preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads, and was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Prince, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, and Celine Dion.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Korg M1 presets were widely used in 1990s house music, beginning with Madonna's 1990 single "Vogue".
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are common in film and television soundtracks.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1969, Mort Garson used a Moog to compose a soundtrack for the televised footage of the Apollo 11 moonwalk, creating a link between electronic music and space in the American popular imagination.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP synthesizers were used to create sound effects for the 1977 science fiction films *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* and *Star Wars*, including the voice of the robot R2-D2.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s and 1980s, synthesizers were used in the scores for thrillers and horror films including *A Clockwork Orange* (1971), *Apocalypse Now* (1979), *The Fog* (1980) and *Manhunter* (1986).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Brad Fiedel used a Prophet synthesizer to record the soundtrack for *The Terminator* (1984), and the filmmaker John Carpenter used them extensively for his soundtracks.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were used to create themes for television shows including *Knight Rider* (1982)*, Twin Peaks* (1990) and *Stranger Things* (2016).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The rise of the synthesizer led to major changes in the music industry, including job displacement, comparable to the 1920s arrival of sound in film, which put live musicians accompanying silent films out of work.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With its ability to imitate instruments such as strings and horns, the synthesizer threatened the jobs of session musicians by allowing one keyboardist or music programmer to produce the same range of sounds as an entire orchestra.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] For a period, the Moog was banned from use in union work, a restriction negotiated by the American Federation of Musicians (AFM).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The musician Walter Sear persuaded the AFM that the synthesizer demanded skill, and the category of *synthesizer player* was accepted into the union.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, players were subject to "suspicion and hostility" for years.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1982, following a tour by Barry Manilow using synthesizers instead of an orchestra, the British Musicians' Union attempted to ban synthesizers, attracting controversy.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, a few musicians skilled at programming the Yamaha DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers generate audio through various forms of analog and digital synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Oscillators produce waveforms (such as sawtooth, sine, or pulse waves) with different timbres.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Voltage-controlled amplifiers (VCAs) control the volume or gain of the audio signal.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] VCAs can be modulated by other components, such as LFOs and envelopes.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A VCA is a preamp that boosts (amplifies) the electronic signal before passing it on to an external or built-in power amplifier, as well as a means to control its amplitude (volume) using an attenuator.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The gain of the VCA is affected by a *control voltage* (CV), coming from an envelope generator, an LFO, the keyboard or some other source.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Envelopes control how sounds change over time.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They may control parameters such as amplitude (volume), filters (frequencies), or pitch.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Low-frequency oscillators (LFOs) produce waveforms used to modulate parameters, such as the pitch of oscillators (producing vibrato).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters remove frequencies from the audio signal, similarly to equalization, to shape sounds.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They typically include controls to set the point at which frequencies are attenuated, and to add resonance.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Common types include low-pass filters, which remove audio above a specified frequency, and high-pass filters, which do the opposite.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters may be controlled with envelopes or LFOs.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Arpeggiators take input chords and convert them into arpeggios.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They usually include controls for speed, range and mode (the movement of the arpeggio).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are often controlled with electronic or digital keyboards or MIDI controller keyboards, which may be built into the synthesizer unit or attached via connections such as CV/gate, USB, or MIDI.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Keyboards may offer expression such as velocity sensitivity and aftertouch, allowing for more control over the sound.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer clones are unlicensed recreations of previous synthesizers, often marketed as affordable versions of famous musical equipment.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Clones are available as physical instruments and software.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Companies that have sold software clones include Arturia and Native Instruments.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Behringer manufactures equipment modelled on instruments including the Minimoog, Pro-One, and TB-303, and drum machines such as the TR-808.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Other synthesizer clones include the MiniMOD (a series of Eurorack modules based on the Minimoog), the Intellijel Atlantis (based on the SH-101), and the x0x Heart (based on the TB-303).
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Creating clones of older hardware is legal where the patents have expired.
[src:fm-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1997, Mackie lost their lawsuit against Behringer as copyright law in the United States did not cover their circuit board designs.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The **Yamaha DX7** is a synthesizer introduced by Yamaha Corporation in 1983.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] It was the first successful digital synthesizer and is one of the best-selling synthesizers in history, selling more than 200,000 units.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In the early 1980s, the synthesizer market was dominated by analog synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Frequency modulation synthesis, a means of generating sounds via frequency modulation (FM), was developed by John Chowning at Stanford University, California.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] FM synthesis created brighter, glassier sounds, and could better imitate acoustic sounds such as brass and bells.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Yamaha licensed the technology to create the DX7, combining it with very-large-scale integration chips to lower manufacturing costs.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] With its complex menus and lack of conventional controls, few learned to program the DX7 in depth.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] However, its preset sounds became staples of 1980s pop music; in 1986, it was used in 40% of the number-one singles on the US *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Its electric piano sound was particularly widely used, especially in power ballads.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The English musician Brian Eno was proficient at programming his own sounds, and it was instrumental to his work in ambient music.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Chips based on the DX7 sound chip, such as the YM2612, were used in technologies such as the Sega Genesis game console.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The DX7 was succeeded by FM synthesizers including the DX1, DX21, DX27 and DX100.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In later years, its sounds came to be seen as dated or clichéd and its use declined.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In 2015, Yamaha released a smaller FM synthesizer, the Reface DX.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] By the mid-20th century, frequency modulation (FM), a means of carrying sound, had been understood for decades and was widely used to broadcast radio transmissions.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In the 1960s, at Stanford University, California, John Chowning developed FM synthesis, a means of using FM to generate sounds that differed from subtractive synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In 1971, to demonstrate its commercial potential, Chowning used FM to emulate acoustic sounds such as organs and brass.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Stanford patented the technology and hoped to license it, but was turned down by American companies including Hammond and Wurlitzer.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Chowning felt their engineers did not understand FM.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] At the time, the Japanese company Yamaha was the world's largest manufacturer of musical instruments but had little market share in the United States.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] One of their chief engineers visited Stanford to view the technology.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] According to Chowning, "In ten minutes he understood ...
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] I guess Yamaha had already been working in the digital domain, so he knew exactly what I was saying." Yamaha licensed the technology for one year to determine its commercial viability, and in 1973 its organ division began developing a prototype FM monophonic synthesizer, assisted by Chowning.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In 1975, Yamaha negotiated exclusive rights for the technology.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Ikutaro Kakehashi, the founder of the Japanese company Roland, was also interested, but met Chowning six months after Yamaha had agreed to the deal.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Kakehashi later said Yamaha were the natural partners in the venture, as they had the resources to make FM synthesis commercially viable.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Yamaha created the first hardware implementation of FM synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The first commercial FM synthesizer was the Yamaha GS1, released in 1980, which was expensive to manufacture due to its integrated circuit chips.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] At the same time, Yamaha was developing the means to manufacture very-large-scale integration chips.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] These allowed the DX7 to use only two chips, compared to the GS1's 50.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Yamaha also altered the implementation of the FM algorithms in the DX7 for efficiency and speed, producing a sampling rate higher than Stanford's synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Chowning felt this produced a noticeable "brilliant" sound.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Yamaha displayed a prototype of the DX7 in 1982, branded the CSDX in reference to the Yamaha CS range of analog synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In late 1982, Dave Bristow and Gary Leuenberger, experts on the Yamaha CS-80, flew to Japan to develop the DX7's voices.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] They had less than four days to create the DX7's 128 preset patches.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Compared to the "warm" and "fuzzy" sounds of analog synthesizers, the DX7 sounds "harsh", "glassy" and "chilly", with a richer, brighter sound.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Its presets constitute "struck" and "plucked" sounds with complex transients.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Its keyboard has five octaves, and the keyboard expression allows for velocity sensitivity and aftertouch.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The DX7 has 16-note polyphony, meaning 16 notes can sound simultaneously.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] It has 32 sound-generating algorithms, each a different arrangement of its six sine wave operators.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The DX7 was the first synthesizer with a liquid-crystal display and the first to allow users to name patches.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Its cartridge slot allows users to share patches.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The DX7 was the first commercially successful digital synthesizer.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] According to Bristow, Yamaha had hoped to sell more than 20,000 units.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Within a year, orders exceeded 150,000 units, and Yamaha sold 200,000 in three years.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] It remains one of the bestselling synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 units.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Yamaha manufactured units on a scale American competitors could not match; by comparison, the American company Moog sold 12,000 Minimoog synthesizers in 11 years, and could not meet demand.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The FM patent was for years one of Stanford's highest earning.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Chowning received royalties for all of Yamaha's FM synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] According to Dave Smith, the founder of the American synthesizer company Sequential, the synthesizer industry was "tiny" in the 1970s, which changed with the DX7.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Smith said it sold well as it was reasonably priced, had keyboard expression and 16 voices, and was better at emulating acoustic sounds than competing products.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Chowning credited the success to the combination of his FM patent with Yamaha's chip technology.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] At the time of release, the DX7 was the first digital synthesizer most musicians had used.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] It differed from the analog synthesizers that had dominated the market; according to *MusicRadar*, its "spiky" and "crystalline" sounds made it "the perfect antidote to a decade of analog waveforms".
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] It was praised for its accuracy in reproducing tubular bells, metallophones and the harpsichord, and took over the electric piano market.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] With complex submenus displayed on an LCD and no knobs and sliders to adjust the sound, many found the DX7 difficult to program.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] *MusicRadar* described its interface as "nearly impenetrable", with "operators, algorithms and unusual envelopes ... accessed through tedious menus and a diminutive display".
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Rather than create their own sounds, most users used the presets.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The Japanese musician Ryuichi Sakamoto was an early user, on Mari Iijima's 1983 album *Rosé* and his 1984 solo album *Ongaku Zukan*.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The DX7 was widely used in 1980s pop music, in hits such as "When Doves Cry" by Prince, "The Best" by Tina Turner, "Smooth Operator" by Sade and "Smooth Criminal" by Michael Jackson.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The "Bass 1" preset was used in songs such as "Take On Me" by A-ha, "Danger Zone" by Kenny Loggins, and "Fresh" by Kool & the Gang.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The "E Piano 1" preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads; it was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, Celine Dion and George Michael, and in the theme tune of the television series *Twin Peaks*.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In 1986, the preset was used in 40% of the number-one singles on the US *Billboard* Hot 100, 40% of country number ones, and 60% of R&B number ones.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The preset imitates a Rhodes piano, prompting some to abandon the Rhodes in favor of the DX7.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] A few musicians skilled at programming the DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The English musician Brian Eno learned to program the DX7 in depth and used it to create ambient music on his 1983 album *Apollo: Atmospheres and Soundtracks*.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] He shared instructions for recreating his patches in a 1987 issue of *Keyboard*.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Eno used the DX7 on records he produced by U2 and Coldplay.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In later years, the DX7 sounds came to be seen as dated or clichéd, and interest in FM synthesis declined, with second-hand digital synthesizers selling for less than analog.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] The development of software synthesizers such as Native Instruments FM8 led to a resurgence in the popularity of FM synthesis.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In the mid-1980s, Yamaha released numerous cheaper FM synthesizers.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] A desktop module version, the TX7, was released in 1985.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] In 1987, Yamaha released the DX7II, which did not match the success of the DX7.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Further successors included the TX81Z, DX1, DX11, and DX21.
[src:fm-synthesis/yamaha-dx7] Yamaha manufactured reduced versions of the DX7 sound chip, such as the YM2612, for use in technologies such as the Sega Genesis game console.
